resources.string: "A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has no positive divisors other than 1 and itself."
"A composite number is a positive integer greater than 1 that has at least one divisor other than 1 and itself."
"A palindrome number reads the same forward and backward."
"A Niven number (or Harshad number) is divisible by the sum of its digits."
"An Emirp number is a prime number that produces a different prime number when its digits are reversed."
"An abundant number is a number for which the sum of its proper divisors is greater than the number itself."
"A Tech number is a number whose digit-by-digit sum is equal to the number itself."
"A Disarium number is a number defined by the sum of its digits raised to their respective positions."
"A pronic number is a number which is the product of two consecutive integers."
"An automorphic number is a number whose square ends with the number itself."
"A Kaprekar number is a number whose square when divided into two parts and such that sum of parts is equal to the original number."
"A special number is a number that has special properties or characteristics."
"A Lucas number is a number in a sequence named after Ã‰douard Lucas."
"A Smith number is a composite number for which the sum of its digits is equal to the sum of the digits of its prime factors."
"An Armstrong number (or narcissistic number) is a number that is the sum of its own digits each raised to the power of the number of digits."
"A Fibonacci number is a number in the sequence of Fibonacci numbers where each number is the sum of the two preceding ones."
"A circular prime number is a prime number that remains prime under cyclic shifts of its digits."
"A prime palindrome number is both a prime number and a palindrome."
"A Fermat number is a positive integer of the form 2^(2^n) + 1, where n is a nonnegative integer."
"An ugly number is a positive integer whose only prime factors are 2, 3, or 5."
"A neon number is a number where the sum of its digits, when squared, equals the number itself."
"A spy number is a number for which the sum of its digits equals the product of its digits."
"A happy number is a number which eventually reaches 1 when replaced by the sum of the square of its digits in each step of iteration."
"A duck number is a number that has at least one zero in it, but when zero or zeros are removed, the resulting number is not zero."
